06079nam a22008295i 9781782381747DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97817823817477 a10.1515/97817823817472doi  a(DE-B1597)637122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD16.2b.N29 2005 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a907/.122304aThe Nation, Europe, and the World :bTextbooks and Curricula in Transition /ced. by Hanna Schissler, Yasemin Nuhoglu Soysal. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Teaching beyond the National Narrative -- tPart I: Europe Contested -- t1. Projections of Identity in French and German History and Civics Textbooks -- t2. Privileged Migrants in Germany, France, and the Netherlands: Return Migrants, Repatriates, and Expellees after 1945 -- t3. What Counts as History and How Much Does History Count? The Case of French Secondary Education -- t4. The Decline and Rise of the Nation in German History Education -- tPart II: Europe Seen from the Periphery -- t5. Nation and the Other in Greek and Turkish History Textbooks -- t6. “Europe” in Bulgarian Conceptions of Nationhood -- t7. Learning about Europe and the World: Schools, Teachers, and Textbooks in Russia after 1991 -- t8. Europe in Spanish Textbooks: a Vague Image in the Space of Memory -- tPart III: Global Frameworks and Approaches to World History -- t9. World History and General Education: How to Bring the World into the Classroom -- t10. Cartographies of Connection: Ocean Maps as Metaphors for Inter-Area History -- t11. World History: Making Sense of the Present -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTextbooks in history, geography and the social sciences provide important insights into the ways in which nation-states project themselves. Based on case studies of France, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, Greece, Turkey Bulgaria, Russia, and the United States, this volume shows the role that concepts of space and time play in the narration of ‘our country’ and the wider world in which it is located. It explores ways in which in western European countries the nation is reinterpreted through European lenses to replace national approaches in the writing of history. On the other hand, in an effort to overcome Eurocentric views,’world history’ has gained prominence in the United States. Yet again, East European countries, coming recently out of a transnational political union, have their own issues with the concept of nation to contend with. These recent developments in the field of textbooks and curricula open up new and fascinating perspectives on the changing patterns of the re-positioning process of nation-states in West as well as Eastern Europe and the United States in an age of growing importance of transnational organizations and globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aHistoryxStudy and teaching. 0aHistoryxTextbooks. 0aInternational educationxCurricula. 0aPlace-based educationxCurricula. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh1 aAntoniou, Vasilia Lilian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertilotti, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDierkes, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeyer, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHymans, Jacques E. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuzón, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular